#AD The perfect winter cocktail features my favourite festive drink @baileysofficial . Bringing all the friends and family together this Christmas time to enjoy a Baileys Hot Chocolate Martini Choctail.

Here’s how to make your own…
Ingredients:
* 25ml Baileys Original Irish Cream (0.4 units)
* 25ml Whole Milk
* 25ml Single Cream
* 25g Dark Chocolate
* 
* 15ml Smirnoff Vodka (0.7 units)
* Chocolate Sauce
* Chocolate Sprinkles
Instructions:
 * Squeeze chocolate sauce onto a small plate
 * Dip the rim of your martini glass in the chocolate sauce
 * On another plate, pour some chocolate sprinkles and coat the chocolate rim in sprinkles
 * Chop/grate 25g of dark chocolate into small pieces
 * Add 25ml of Whole Milk and 25ml of Single Cream into a mug, mix, and microwave for around 30 seconds until boiling. Keep an eye on it so it doesn’t spill over
 * Add the chopped dark chocolate to the hot milk & cream and stir until melted
 * Then add 15ml Smirnoff Vodka and 25ml Baileys Original Irish Cream into your chocolate milk
 * Stir until fully combined. It doesn’t matter if your cocktail is still a little warm, we like it this way!
 * Pour into your decorated martini glass and serve. If you have spare chocolate, grate it over the top for an extra treat!

perfectly imperfect. 

I was sat by the pool yesterday and it got me thinking. Thinking about my body and about insecurities - things we try to cover, hide or change. My own insecurities to be specific: my “thick” thighs, scars, my skin, cellulite, spots, stretch marks, bloating, tummy rolls - just to name a few.  These are all things I pick apart when I see certain angles, photos and clips of myself. 

However - we have to remember that most of the time these insecurities stem from societal “ideals” we have survived through! My teenage years were filled with a rhetoric that womens bodies need to be nip,tucked, photoshopped, smoothed or erased if it didn’t fit the current standard of beauty. (Which is EVER changing its actually hard to keep up with 😅)

Speaking from my own perspective - I’m not expecting to “love” all my insecurities. I believe that sets an unrealistic ideal for ourselves.  I’m just saying it’s ok to ACCEPT them. And that is a place I can comfortably say I am approaching. I also feel it’s very easy to assume the idea that we are alone on this journey. But we are not. No matter what “size” someone is we all suffer with our own critical feelings towards ourselves. You may view someone and long for their beautiful hair, clear skin, flat stomach or long legs - however that doesn’t mean they don’t suffer with their own insecurities surrounding themselves. I recently found a terrifying statistic that I needed to share with you, one study found that 63% of female participants identified weight as the key factor in determining how they felt about themselves – more important than family, school, or career. This has to change. We have to value ourselves for things outside of our bodies. And we also HAVE to start altering how we perceive and project standards of beauty. I know my page is only small but at times I find myself a part of the problem - using filters on stories, scared to show my skin when it’s spotty - only posting flattering angles and bikini shots. All of which I need to start undoing in the year 2023. Why don’t you join me on this journey? Let’s start accepting who we are - every. single. part. ♥️

Some of my favourite photos ever. ♥️👙🤿☀️
Every single one of them. 
Even those that by society’s standards are not as “flattering” - to me I was having the best time and these photos will forever remind me of the amazing memories created on this trip! 

I feel there is such a pressure on women to either look perfect or be “real” and “vulnerable” 24/7. Why can’t both of these things coexist? I feel that the first set of photos made me feel confident and I loved how they turned out! But I equally love the last snap of me — fun,happy,smiley and natural! With all my rolls out!! Just having fun and enjoying the moment ♥️ 

This is just a reminder that social media is always constructed - sometimes even those images that appear the most “real” are not! And that is 100% ok. We need to stop having such pressures on ourselves - if you want to post the perfect photo -  DO IT and if you want to show a more vulnerable side then that’s also amazing and deserves to be celebrated. ♥️♥️ One is not better than the other - at the end of the day Instagram is a snippet of your life and if you want to show your highlight reel good for you! And if you want to show real struggles I love that too as it helps so many of us! I love you all and I hope my page shows you the good moments alongside those real moments too. ♥️♥️♥️

The week I had my first panic attack. You’d never of guessed from these photos! I don’t have to mention it and it has absolutely nothing to do with what I usually post here but I don’t know - my page feels like sort of an online diary and this may help one of you out there. I also feel the more honest and open I am with you the closer we all become. From these photos you’d of had absolutely no idea. My week looks perfect. And it was I am so grateful for my incredible life - but I did have this tiny moment. A small stumble. This tiny moment that felt like an eternity. Anxiety cannot be shown through a photo. So let this be a reminder that social media shows a snapshot of a moment - a millisecond - a tiny fragment of time. It’s crazy to think that we see images & videos of people online where everything can seem perfect  but the reality is that we have no idea what is really going on outside of that split second. I can’t lie - it was honestly a horrendous feeling - I felt like I was dying 😅 (i realise how crazy that sounds in hindsight but in the moment it felt so real.) 
The experience was totally humiliating -  in the middle of the gym  unable to breathe (and no it wasn’t because I’m very unfit 😅) but if 10 people in the gym saw me like that why not share it with all you 🤣— maybe it can help those of you feel less alone.
I’m just about to walk back into the gym. I will not let this moment cast a shadow over the rest of my week - my month - my life. I’m sure moments like this may happen again and I cannot be naive to that . However, knowing that I can cope with it and those feelings of anxiety will pass is helpful. I know at time I can seem like the happiest person on social media - and honestly 99% of the time I am so positive and so happy! But don’t be fooled into thinking that social media shows everything - it really doesn’t.  We all have our highs and lows - but for most of us we don’t capture those lows. You are not alone - I hope this reassures some of you out there that those feelings are temporary. We’ve got this! ♥️💭

ok a few of you have been asking what am I doing to keep my hair in the best condition and try and repair it from years of bleaching, extensions and heat damage!!!! And I’ve found the perfect routine 💘💖💗

- Pre- wash routine: 
This was something I had never even considered until recently! I always do a pre wash to stimulate my scalp and get the blood flowing! I also love to use a diluted rosemary oil on the scalp with a massager to encourage the hair! In addition to this I will ALWAYS use something on the rest of the hair - lately I have not stopped using the @philip_kingsley elasticizer because it is incredible! ✨ But any deep conditioner or oil will be great on the ends to keep them nice and healthy! 

- Hair wash routine: 
I’ve been loving the @philip_kingsley volume shampoo and purple shampoo & conditioner! But I also use @vegamour which smells gorgeous - and then this new @goldwelluki purple conditioner has been amazing to keep my recent colour! 🛀🏼

- Post hair wash: 
I’d only recommend using contiioner if you are going to skip this next step! And that is @k18hair_uk … guys I cannot rave about this stuff enough! It has completely changed my hair - for the better! I am so so impressed! And then sometimes I will go in with @colorwowhair dream coat or @redken heat protectant! 

- Using heat… 
In a dream world I would leave the hair to air dry and I do try and do this often! However the overnight curls will not work on hair that is too wet! So I dry my hair 90% using my @dysonhair 🌸 I then use my overnight curler - this one is from @amazon but I am so desperate to try the more expensive ones as I’ve heard they are comfortable to sleep in! I wrap a piece of hair around the curler adding small sections as I go! The smaller the pieces the tighter the curls - I also try and grab the hair as fast as I can so that I don’t just end up curling the ends! I then tie the curler together and leave it to set overnight! 💓

- the next morning… 
Once I wake up I take out the curler and brush through the curls - I find that I can do this because the curls have set so nicely they will not drop out! I add a bit of hair oil and that is it! 💗💗
